-- Sub-Saharan African Equities: Cal Bank, Co-Operative Bank, Guaranty, Wema
-- B y   E r i c   O m b o k
-- 2010-10-22T13:14:00Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-10-22/sub-saharan-africa-stocks-east-african-breweries-harel-freres-are-active.html
Kenya’s  All-Share Index  advanced the
most in more than a month, rising 1 percent to 84.19 by the 3
p.m. close in Nairobi. That’s the highest since July 25, 2008.  Mauritius’s  SEMDEX Index  snapped four days of declines,
adding 0.1 percent to 1,841.54 by the 1:30 p.m. close in Port
Louis. The measure fell for the first week in three, dropping
1.4 percent.  The  Nigeria Stock Exchange All Share Index  rose for the
first time in four days, climbing 1.8 percent to 24,986.87 by
12:34 p.m. in Lagos, while the  Namibia Overall Index  fell 0.9
percent to 830.23 by 2:43 p.m. in Windhoek, the first drop in
three days. The  Ghana All Share Index  retreated less than 0.1
percent to 6,860.4 by 12:43 p.m. in Accra.  The following shares rose or fell in sub-Saharan Africa,
excluding South Africa. Stock symbols are in parentheses.  Cal Bank Ltd.  (CAL GN), a Ghanaian lender, rose the most in
more than a week, increasing 1 pesewa, or 3.6 percent, to 29
pesewas. Profit for the nine months through September climbed 27
percent to 7.54 million cedis ($5.28 million), from a year
earlier the bank said in a statement published in the Ghanaian
Times newspaper today.  Co-Operative Bank of Kenya Ltd.  (COOP KN) added 20 cents,
or 1 percent, to 20 shillings, the highest since Dec. 22, 2008,
when its shares started trading. The stock climbed on
speculation profit for the nine months through September will
grow at a similar rate as in the first half, James Mose, a
research analyst at Nairobi-based CFC Stanbic Financial Services
Ltd., said in a phone interview today. Kenya’s fourth-biggest
lender by assets reports third-quarter earnings on Oct. 26.  First-half profit surged 60 percent to 2.34 billion
shillings ($29 million) from a year earlier, the company said on
Aug. 16.  East African Breweries Ltd.  (EABL KN), Diageo Plc’s Kenyan
unit, advanced 4 shillings, or 2 percent, to 208 shillings, a
fifth day of gains. The company’s shareholders approved its
purchase of a 51 percent stake in Serengeti Breweries Ltd. of
Tanzania, the company said in an e-mailed statement yesterday.  Guaranty Trust Bank Plc  (GUARANTY NL), Nigeria’s third-
biggest lender by market value, rose the most since May, adding
78 kobo, or 5 percent, to 16.54 naira after the Punch newspaper
reported that shareholders approved a plan for the lender to
sell its non-banking units.  The bank can proceed with the sale of GT Assurance Plc, GTB
Asset Management Ltd., and GTB Registrars, the Lagos-based
newspaper said, citing chairman Oluwole Oduyemi. The company
will sell the units to comply with central bank requirements, it
said.  Kenya Commercial Bank Ltd.  (KNCB KN), the East African
nation’s biggest lender by assets and outlets, advanced for the
first time in seven trading days, adding 25 cents, or 1.1
percent, to 22.75 shillings.  Third-quarter profit climbed 29 percent to 4.5 billion
shillings in the three months through September, from 3.5
billion shillings the same period a year earlier, the lender
said in a statement e-mailed by the Nairobi Stock Exchange
yesterday.  Harel Freres Ltd.  (HFRERES MP), which produces 75 percent
of Mauritius’s processed sugar, fell 0.1 rupee, or 0.3 percent,
to 35.9 rupees, the third decline this week. The company’s board
recommended a merger with Saint Andre Sugar Estate Co. and wants
to complete the transaction by Dec. 31, it in a statement
yesterday.  For each share held, Saint Andre shareholders will receive
1,065 Harel Freres shares and 3,100 rupees if the transaction is
approved, the company said.  Wema Bank Plc  (WEMABANK NL), one of Nigerian lenders that
failed an audit by the central bank last year, rallied to the
highest since Sept. 8, increasing 4 kobo, or 4.3 percent, to 97
kobo, after it reported a return to profitability in the nine
months through September.  Net income for the period was 1.64 billion naira ($10.8
million), compared with a loss of 29.7 billion naira a year
earlier, the company said in an e-mailed statement from the
Nigerian Stock Exchange yesterday.  To contact the reporter on this story:
